iskr</i> ‘fish’ + <i>-e</i> from <i>vin</i> ‘meadow’.","English (East Anglia): variant of   Fisk  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Fisk","meanings":["English (East Anglia): metonymic occupational name for a fisherman or fish seller, or a nickname for someone supposedly resembling a fish in some way, from Old Norse <i>fiskr</i> ‘fish’ (cognate with Old English <i>fisc</i>). See   Fish   1."]}]},{"name":"Daniel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name (meaning ‘God is my judge’ in Hebrew), borne by the prophet whose story is told in the Book of Daniel. He was an Israelite slave of the Assyrian king Nebuchadnezzar, who obtained great favour through his skill in interpreting dreams and the ‘writing on the wall’ at the feast held by Nebuchadnezzar's son Belshazzar. His enemies managed to get him cast into a lions' den, but he was saved by God. This was a favourite tale in the Middle Ages, often represented in miracle plays. The name has been perennially popular among English speakers since the 16th century and has been particularly favoured since the 1980s."],"variants":[{"name":"Danyal","meanings":["Fanciful respelling of   Daniel ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":23,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Daniel Fiske was born in April 1358, in Laxfield, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, Hugh Daniel Fiske, was 18 and his mother, Mrs. Hugh Fiske, was 17. He married Adwin in 1378, in Laxfield, Suffolk, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons an